# mrcall-cs — Campaign Tick

Execute ALL steps below silently. **Do not address the operator until the
tick is complete** — the next user-visible text is the final report in
step 4. "Silently" means tool calls are fine, narration is not. If a step
fails, capture a one-line note and continue; the report has an `Anomalie:`
slot.

Your job: advance every active campaign one step, per the worklist the
verbs hand you. You do NOT decide policy — the verbs do (draft-vs-send,
dedup, rate-cap, kill-switch are all inside them). You read replies,
classify the human message, and route. **You are Opus here on purpose
(Mario: "OPUS, l'avevo detto") — TEMPORARY**; a leaner deterministic
`campaign tick` verb replaces this later. Do not build that now.

All commands run from the repo root with `.venv/bin/python -m cs …`.

## 0. Hard rules (read before acting)

- **Identity is ALWAYS `{{ email_address }}`.** Enforced by the engine
  (`token.sub == OWNER_ID`) and by {{ email_address }}'s own credentials — you cannot
  and must not act as anyone else. Never sign, never compose, as anyone but
  {{ email_address }}.
- **DEFAULT ON UNCERTAINTY = ESCALATE.** When a reply is ambiguous, out of
  scope, angry, or you are not sure: leave the contact untouched and list it
  under "Escalations (need you):". Never auto-confirm, never auto-send a
  free-form reply, never re-mail. A missed nudge is cheap; a wrong send is not.
- **Autoresponder ≠ a real reply.** "richiesta ricevuta / your request has
  been taken up / Auto-replay / Ciao MrCaller! / out-of-office / studio OOO"
  is NOT engagement and NOT a confirmation. Never treat it as a reply worth
  answering or closing on.
- **Re-classify only on a NEWER reply.** Re-LLM a contact's reply only when a
  reply arrived that is newer than the last one you classified
  (`dossier.classified_upto`). Do not re-reason the same message every run.
- **NEVER invent facts.** Use only what is in the thread + engine memory. No
  prices, dates, promises, or capabilities the record does not contain.
- **The {{ excluded_campaign }} campaign is EXCLUDED.** `{{ excluded_campaign }}` is
  owned by a dedicated process. `cs campaign pending` already drops it, but never
  act on it here regardless.
- **Free-form replies go through the engine** via `cs draft-reply …`, never
  cs-SMTP, never `cs chat --allow` (denied to you by permission). It stores a
  DRAFT and CANNOT send — sending is the operator's job. You only ever draft.

## 1. List the campaigns

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs campaign list
```

Note the active campaigns + their per-state counts. The `{{ excluded_campaign }}`
campaign is **out of scope** — a dedicated process owns it. Work every OTHER
campaign.

## 2. Pull each campaign's worklist

For each campaign that is **not** `{{ excluded_campaign }}`:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs campaign pending --name <campaign-name>
```

Returns JSON: `campaigns[].items[]`, each item carrying an `action`
(`reconcile` / `send_draft` / `handle_reply`), a `contact_id`, the `email`,
and (for replies) a `thread_id` anchor. The verb sends nothing and mutates
nothing — it is the worklist only. The excluded campaign will not appear; if
it somehow does, skip it.

## 3. Work each item — branch on `action`

### 3a. `action: reconcile`

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs campaign reconcile <contact_id> --commit
```

Corrective only: the mail was already sent out-of-band (e.g. by Mario, by
hand in Gmail), so the `drafted` row is stale. This fixes the state to `sent`
and records the Sent thread. **No mail is sent — safe.** The verb refuses if
no Sent thread exists (it never invents a send), so trust its result. Record
the outcome for the report.

### 3b. `action: send_draft`

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs campaign queue-draft <contact_id> --commit
```

Composed-draft outreach: a personalized mail already written on the contact.
`queue-draft` is dedup-first (refuses + flags `reconcile` if the address is
already in the Sent archive) and **only ever surfaces the mail to {{ email_address }}'s
Gmail Drafts — it never sends** (the send-capable `send-draft` verb is denied
to you by permission). Read its JSON result: if it returns `next: reconcile`
/ `already in Sent`, run step 3a for that contact instead. Never hand-compose
or reach for SMTP. Record the outcome.

### 3c. `action: handle_reply`

A customer thread has a reply after our send. **Read the FULL thread, bodies
not snippets** — snippets routinely show {{ company_display_name }}'s OWN autoresponder, not the
human:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.list_by_thread '{"thread_id":"<thread_id>"}'
```

The result is `{"emails":[…]}` (a dict, not a list). Read the message
**bodies**; find the newest HUMAN message. If it is not newer than
`dossier.classified_upto` (visible on the contact via `cs campaign pending`),
it is already classified — leave it, do nothing. Otherwise classify with
judgment and route:

- **Autoresponder / out-of-office / "richiesta ricevuta"** ⇒ NOT a reply
  worth acting on. Leave the contact in track (NO `--state` change), but you
  MUST persist that you saw it AND stamp `classified_upto` to this reply's
  timestamp — otherwise the next tick re-classifies the same autoresponder
  forever (`mark` without `--commit` is a dry-run and saves nothing):
  ```bash
  .venv/bin/python -m cs campaign mark <contact_id> --dossier '{"autoresponder_seen": true, "classified_upto": "<reply ISO timestamp>"}' --commit
  ```
  Dossier-only (state stays `sent`), so the contact remains in track: a future
  GENUINE human reply is newer than `classified_upto` and WILL be picked up.

- **Interested, or a genuine in-scope question / objection you can answer
  from the thread + memory** ⇒ compose a contextual reply **via the engine**
  (memory + trained voice + threading, {{ email_address }}):
  ```bash
  .venv/bin/python -m cs draft-reply "rispondi nel thread con <email>: <breve intento>"
  ```
  `draft-reply` stores a DRAFT and cannot send (the operator reviews & sends).
  Then mark the contact engaged:
  ```bash
  .venv/bin/python -m cs campaign mark <contact_id> --state replied --dossier '{"outcome":"engaged"}' --commit
  ```

- **Clearly not interested** ⇒ close it, no reply:
  ```bash
  .venv/bin/python -m cs campaign mark <contact_id> --state replied --dossier '{"outcome":"declined"}' --commit
  ```

- **Ambiguous, out of scope, angry, or anything you are not sure about** ⇒
  **ESCALATE.** Do NOT auto-answer. Persist the flag so it surfaces in
  `cs review` until the operator clears it, and stamp `classified_upto` so the
  same reply isn't re-escalated every tick:
  ```bash
  .venv/bin/python -m cs campaign mark <contact_id> --dossier '{"escalated": true, "escalate_reason": "<perché: ambiguo / fuori scope / arrabbiato>", "classified_upto": "<reply ISO ts>"}' --commit
  ```
  Also list it under "Escalations (need you):" in the report. The operator
  handles it and clears the flag when done. Default whenever judgment is
  uncertain.

When you do classify a fresh human reply, you may stamp
`classified_upto` to the reply's ISO timestamp via the same `mark
--dossier` call you are already making (merge it into the dossier patch),
so the next tick does not re-classify the same message.

## 4. Report

Now — and only now — address the operator. Italian, founders' register:
tight, complete sentences, no jargon, no emoji, no "fammi sapere". A compact
table of what was done per contact, then an explicit escalation list:

```
mrcall-cs — campaign tick

Campagne lavorate: <names> ({{ excluded_campaign }} esclusa)

| campagna | contatto | azione | esito |
|---|---|---|---|
| … | … | reconcile / send-draft / risposta-in-bozza / chiuso(declined) / autoresponder / lasciato | … |

Escalations (need you):
- <email> — <campagna> — <perché: ambiguo / fuori scope / arrabbiato / incerto>

Anomalie: <una riga per nota; ometti se nessuna>
```

The action column reflects what the verbs actually did (read their JSON
results — e.g. a `send-draft` that flipped to `reconcile`, a draft already in
Gmail). If "Escalations (need you):" is empty, write `nessuna`. Surface every
contact you touched and every one you deliberately left.
